John Edward: Language skills are essential for the citizens of the world
Scotland's independent schools maintain a record of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with new excellent exam results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools work to prepare their students for higher education, for the career they have chosen and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector capable of designing and implementing a tailor-made school curriculum, we find that contemporary languages remain popular and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, you speak to his heart.”
This reminds us that we cannot rely on English to build relationships and establish a trusting bond with people from other countries.
Looking at the excellent test scores this year, we see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received the highest score, A.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, show that 72% of students obtained the highest grade, A, in Mandarin, as did the 72% of students who studied German, the 69% of students who studied French and the 63% of students who studied Spanish.
This shows that Scotland's independent schools support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and young people in the future.
Now, languages as subjects are organized just like science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the programs of independent schools and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills found that, among the difficulties employers face in recruiting candidates, 17% are linked to language skills shortages.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job offers requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
Regardless of your career choice, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real advantage in the future thanks to this sustainable skill.
Being able to communicate directly with foreigners will automatically put the multilingual person in front of his competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults living in the UK, 75% of them did not speak enough foreign language to hold a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15%).
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, including those of emerging economies, children will have a better chance of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Many of them will focus on classical contemporary languages, while others will teach languages considered important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, including Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever your child’s preferences, several languages will be accessible in independent schools, with specialist staff in the field.
Scottish independent schools want to offer a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds for them.
It is clear that, at the present time, in a global business environment, languages remain of paramount importance for the country's future, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
It has to be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
