North Korea says that disarmament will under no circumstances be done unilaterally without confidence.
On Saturday, the North Korean foreign minister told the United Nations that maintaining sanctions would strengthen his distrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons in these circumstances.
At the World Organization’s annual General Assembly, Ri Yong Ho said North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” last year, such as ending nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and its commitment not to proliferate weapons and technology.
“However, we do not see any corresponding response from the United States,” he said.
“In the absence of confidence in the United States, we will fear for our national security and, under such circumstances, it is excluded that we will be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While reiterating North Korea’s well-known criticism of Washington’s opposition to a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it gradually took action, its statement proved to be important in that it did not reject the idea of denuclearization as a denuclearization by Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made on June 12 in Singapore at the very first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work for a “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised to ensure North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking to formally end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also rejected calls to ease severe international sanctions against North Korea.
The United States insists that North Korea first proceed to denuclearization and escalates the pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve their goal in a coercive manner, even opposing “the declaration of an end to the war.”
“Those who think that these sanctions can make us collapse do not know us.
The problem is that maintaining sanctions increases our mistrust.”
Ri made no comment on the second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader highlighted before the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings that have taken place between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the party concerned with the issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a stalemate.”
Still, Ri’s tone of speech was radically different from last year’s when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to point North Korean missiles at North American territory after the “evil” President Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who had threatened last year before the United Nations to “totally destroy” North Korea, did not praise this year for Kim’s courage in implementing disarmament measures, but added that there was still much to be done and that sanctions would not be lifted until North Korea disarmed.
On Wednesday, Trump said no deadline had been set. “It can take two years, three years or five months; it doesn’t matter,” he said.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “the application of Security Council sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until total, definitive and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to suffocate funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the United Nations General Assembly and then announced that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang claiming that progress had been made but, in the hours that followed, North Korea denounced his “gangster methods.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the United States took “equivalent measures.”
According to the South Korean president, Kim is calling for the security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore, and efforts to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard: students take rest classes
This year, Harvard University has set up a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fight the growing male tendency to study by consuming caffeine all night.
A professor noticed that most students at the best university in the world don’t know how to take care of them.
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him.
At the end, a student approached me and said, “Why am I only told this in the last year?”
She claimed that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
Delivered for the first time this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s director general of health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students were suffering from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The class time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to learn the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know this won’t instantly change student behavior.
However, in our view, they have the right to know this information – in the same way that you have the right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride of “spending a white night” still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure exerted on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Having enough and good quality sleep should be the “secret weapon” of students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said — even to avoid gaining weight, because lack of sleep puts the brain in starvation mode, making them hungry constantly.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student in chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and pushed him to insist that it be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar degree program before joining the renowned institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to provide an alarm for both bedtime and wakefulness, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleep disorders.
