World Wide Web Inventor Plans to Launch New Internet to Challenge Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a brand new company that seeks to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of Berners-Lee’s free platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored as well as people authorized to access such or such information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt aimed to “dominate the world.”
“We have to do it now,” he said of the launch.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid technology to allow people to create their own “online personal data store” or DPL.
It may contain contact lists, to-do lists, a calendar, a music library, as well as other personal and professional tools.
It’s as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available at the same time on a single browser.
The peculiarity of the online personal data store is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access what type of information.
The company calls this “personal responsibility via data.”
According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, Inrupt’s idea is that the company brings appropriate resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to all.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a few developers working on the project, and a community of volunteer coders.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said his team and he are not yet in discussion with “Facebook and Google” about whether or not to make a complete change where all their business models are completely messed up in an instant.
“We don’t ask their permission.”
In an article published Saturday on Medium, Berners-Lee writes that "Inrupt's mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new web built on Solid."
In 1994, at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating the World Wide Web Consortium.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Although he launched Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely optimistic about this new era of the web,” Berners-Lee added.
