The only churchman from the Church of England to have received the Cross of Victoria during the First World War as a fighter was celebrated in his hometown 100 years later.
Lieutenant-Colonel Bernard Vann won this distinction on 29 September 1918, during the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed by an elite sniper four days later and was unaware that he had earned the highest British military distinction.
His two grandsons unveiled a commemorative stone at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, last Saturday.
Michael Vann, one of his grandsons, said it was “brilliantly symbolic” to unveil the stone exactly 100 years after his grandfather’s exploit.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion on the St. Quentin Canal “through a very thick fog and under the violent firing of field guns and machine guns.”
Later, he rushed to the firing line and, with the "greatest bravery", led the line before blowing up a field cannon on his own and smothering three soldiers from the detachment.
On October 4, 1918, a German sniper killed Lieutenant Colonel Vann, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “one thing I’ll never be up to, but that makes me humble.”
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also filed a crown after the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Vann said he was “very honoured to be part of the parade” and added that “the courage of an authentic hero is reflected in the support that will be given to him by many people.”
