It is a regrettable situation.”
Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt “lower” in terms of sexuality
Olympic diver Tom Daley claims to have grown up feeling inferior to others because of his sexuality – but this instilled in him the motivation to succeed.
The 24-year-old said he didn’t realize before going to high school that “everyone [was] not like me.”
In the context of the first Radio 4 show Desert Island Discs presented by Lauren Laverne, he said he spoke about the issue of gay rights to give others “hope”.
He also said that becoming a parent made him less interested in winning the Olympics.
The show's regular host, Kirsty Young, took a months off due to her illness.
Appearing as a wrecker on Laverne's first show, Daley confided that he felt "less than" all the other children growing up because "it was not socially acceptable to love boys and girls."
He said, “Even today, these feelings of being inferior and different are the real things that gave me the power and strength to succeed.”
In order not to disappoint everyone when they finally learned the truth about his sexuality, he wanted to prove that he was “something.”
The double Olympic bronze medallist is now a renowned LGBT activist and has taken advantage of his participation this year at the Commonwealth Games in Australia to ask more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said that he expressed himself because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without ramifications and that he wanted to give “hope” back to others.
The triple world champion claimed that he "didn't expect" to fall in love with a man - American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, met in 2013
Daley last year married the Oscar winner, his 20-year-old eldest, but he said age difference had never been a problem.
“When you live so much at such a young age” – he participated in his first Olympic Games at the age of 14 and his father died of cancer three years later – he says confidently that it was difficult to find a person of the same age having experienced the same ups and downs.
In June, they became parents to a boy named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley claimed that “his whole perspective” had changed.
“If you had asked me last year, I was only thinking of winning a gold medal,” he said.
“You know what, there are things more important than Olympic gold medals.
“My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.”
His son bears the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 from brain cancer.
Daley confided that his father had not accepted that he was going to die and that one of the last things he asked him was if they already had their tickets for London 2012, since he wanted to be sitting in the first row.
“I couldn’t tell him, ‘Dad, you won’t be there to be in the front row anymore,’” he said.
“I held him by the hand when he stopped breathing and he had to stop breathing and he had to die so that I finally recognized that he wasn’t invincible,” he added.
The following year, Daley participated in the 2012 Olympic Games and won a bronze medal.
"That's all I've dreamed of all my life - diving in front of a crowd at home at the Olympics, there's nothing better," he said.
In addition, it inspired her first choice of song - Proud by Heather Small - which had accompanied her in preparations for the Olympics and always gave her the flesh of a chicken.
