Germany's new warship delayed
According to local media, the new German Navy frigate should have been commissioned in 2014 to replace aging Cold War warships, but it will not be in service until at least next year due to faulty systems and exponential spending.
According to the newspaper Die Zeit, which cites a military spokesman, the commissioning of the “Rheinland-Pfalz”, the flagship of the brand-new frigates of Baden-W<0xC3><0xBC>rttemberg, was postponed to the first half of 2019.
The ship should have joined the Navy in 2014, but the worrying problems that occurred after delivery compromised the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-W<0xC3><0xBC>rttemberg-class ships that the Navy ordered in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is certain that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as certain stealth technologies, such as radar signature, infrared and reduced acoustics.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods - it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates for a period of up to two years outside the docking ports.
According to Die Zeit, however, the incessant delays mean that forward-looking warships – which should allow Germany to project its force overseas – will already be obsolete when put into service.
Last year, the cursed F125 frigate made headlines when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after its delivery.
The reasons for this return were little known, but the German media mentioned a number of "software and hardware defects" that rendered the warship useless in the event of deployment on combat missions.
The software flaws were particularly important because the Baden-W<0xC3><0xBC>rttemberg class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, which corresponds to half of the crews of the old Bremen class frigates.
In addition, it appears that the ship is significantly overloaded, which reduces its efficiency and reduces the Navy's ability to make future improvements.
It is estimated that the 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz weighs twice as much as similar-class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Beyond the computer system failures, the price of the project as a whole – including crew training – also becomes a problem.
It is said to have reached the astronomical sum of 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion), compared to 2.2 billion initially.
The problems associated with the new frigates are of particular importance in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval strength is declining.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German Parliament’s defence committee, acknowledged earlier this year that the Navy is actually “short of ships capable of deploying.”
The official said the situation had produced a snowball effect over time, as the old ships were downgraded but no replacement ships were designated.
He regretted that none of the frigates of the Baden-W<0xC3><0xBC>rttemberg class were able to join the Navy.
The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research conducted in a field in the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The National Trust for Scotland researchers' study will follow common pipers and sopranos as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton at the Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
A professional analysis of the sound will determine the frequency of bat calls and the activities of the different species.
A map and habitat report will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important areas of habitat for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as grassland creation and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by the construction and development work that affects the perch and leads to the loss of their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as can flypaper and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as pet cat attacks.
The bats are not really blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to capturing prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to spot insects and obstacles on their flight routes.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly carry out surveys, inspections at the perch and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threeave site in Dumfries-et-Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, manager of the domain, says the site is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threeve, we have a perfect place for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitat.
But there’s still a lot to learn about bats, so the work we’re doing here and elsewhere will help us better understand what bats need to thrive.”
He stressed the importance of verifying the presence of bats before proceeding with the maintenance of the properties, because by unintentionally destroying a single maternity nest, one can thus cause the death of 400 females and small ones, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb, or destroy their perch.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and as far as many of our species are concerned, we don’t know what’s going on in their populations right now.”
