Brexit: The UK would “forever regret” the departure of automakers.
According to Greg Clark, the Secretary of State for Trade, the UK “would regret it forever” if it were to lose its status as a world leader in automotive construction after Brexit.
He added that it was "worrying" that Toyota UK told the BBC that it would temporarily stop production at its plant in Burnaston, near Derby, if Britain withdrew from the EU without a deal.
“We need a deal,” Clark said.
The Japanese automaker said the impact of delays at the border in the event of a no-deal Brexit could cost jobs.
The Burnaston plant - which makes Toyota's Auris and Avensis vehicles - built nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to other European Union countries.
“I believe that if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, production will stop at our factory,” said Marvin Cooke, Toyota’s director in Burnaston.
Other British automakers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have expressed fears of leaving the EU without a deal on the functioning of cross-border trade.
For example, BMW says it will close its Mini factory in Oxford for a month following Brexit.
The biggest concerns are what automakers call risks to the supply chain in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line is operated in "tensioned flow", parts arrive every 37 minutes from UK and EU suppliers for custom-made vehicles.
If the UK leaves the EU without a deal on 29 March, there could be disruptions at the border that industry says could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to hold the inventory for more than a day at its factory in Derbyshire, the company said, and so production would be stopped.
According to Clark, Theresa May’s Chequers plan for future relations with the EU is “precisely calibrated to avoid these border checks.”
"We want to have the best deal that will allow, as I said, not only to enjoy the current success, but also to seize this opportunity," he said on BBC Radio 4's Today.
“The evidence, not just from Toyota but from other manufacturers, is that we absolutely need to be able to maintain what has proven to be an excellent set of supply chains.”
If Toyota was unable to specify how long production would stop, it warned that in the longer term, additional costs would reduce the plant’s competitiveness and eventually cost jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, the Unite union coordinator at the plant and who has been working for 24 years in Burnaston, said its members were increasingly worried: “In my experience, once these jobs disappear, they never come back.”
A government spokesman said: “We have proposed a precise and credible plan for our future relationship with the EU.”
White House Announces Trump and Rosenstein Meeting May Be Delayed
According to the White House’s announcement on Sunday, the meeting, which presents important issues, between Donald Trump and Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could be “rejected by a week,” while the fight for Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh continues.
Rosenstein oversees the work of Robert Mueller, the special counsel charged with investigating Russian interference in the election, the links between Trump’s collaborators and Russia, and possible obstructions to justice exercised by the president.
The question of whether or not Trump will send back the deputy attorney general, and therefore endanger Mueller’s independence, has fueled rumors in Washington for months.
Earlier this month, the New York Times reported that Rosenstein had talked about wearing a microphone to record conversations with Trump and the possibility of eliminating the president by the 25th Amendment.
Rosenstein denied these claims.
However, last Monday, he showed up at the White House, as he was about to resign.
Instead, a meeting with Trump, who was then at the United Nations in New York, was announced Thursday.
Trump said he would “prefer not” to dismiss Mr. Rosenstein, but the meeting was postponed to avoid a confrontation with the Senate Judiciary Committee hearing before which Kavanaugh and Dr. Christine Blasey Ford, one of the women who accused him of sexual assault, testified.
On Friday, Trump asked the FBI to conduct a week-long investigation into complaints against Kavanaugh, further delaying the Senate vote.
On Sunday, Trump’s press secretary, Sarah Sanders, made an appearance at Fox News.
Asked about the meeting with Rosenstein, she said: "No date has been set for this, it could be this week, I could see if we push back another week given all the other things that are going on in the Supreme Court.
