Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp duty if they buy a property in the UK
Foreign buyers will have to pay higher stamp duty if they buy a property in the UK and the extra money will be used to help the homeless under the new Conservative regimes.
This measure will cancel the success of Corbyn’s campaign to attract young voters
The increase in stamp duty will be imposed on those who do not pay tax in the UK
The Treasury expects to raise up to <0xC2><0xA3>120 million a year to help the homeless.
Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp duty rate if they buy a property in the UK – the extra money will be used to help the homeless, Theresa May announced today.
This measure will be seen as an initiative to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn’s campaign to attract young voters by committing to providing more affordable housing and targeting high-income earners.
The increase in stamp duty will be imposed on individuals and businesses who do not pay taxes in the UK, and the extra money will be used to strengthen the government's efforts in the fight to help the homeless.
This surcharge - which is in addition to the current stamp duty, including the higher levels introduced two years ago on secondary residences and rental purchases - could reach 3%.
The Treasury expects the project to raise up to <0xC2><0xA3>120 million a year.
About 13% of new London construction is purchased by non-residents in the UK, which drives up prices and prevents first-time homebuyers from making their way into the housing market.
Many rich areas of the country - especially in the capital - have become "ghost cities" because of the high number of foreign buyers who mostly stay outside the country.
This new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson demanded a reduction in the stamp duty to help more young people acquire a first home.
Accusing major construction companies of keeping real estate prices at a high level by seizing land without using it, he urged Mrs. May to give up quotas on affordable housing in order to address the “real estate disgrace” in the UK.
Mr. Corbyn presented an attractive set of housing reform proposals, including rent control and the removal of “no-fault” evictions.
He also wants to give councils broader powers to build new housing.
May said: “Last year I said I would dedicate my post as Prime Minister to the rebirth of the British dream – that every new generation would have a better life.
To do this, we need to repair our broken housing market.
Britain will always be open to anyone who wants to live, work and build a life here.
However, it is unfair that it is as easy for individuals who do not reside in the UK, as it is for foreign companies, to buy a house as it is for British residents who work hard.
For far too many people, the dream of access to property has become far away and the misery of the homeless remains too real.”
Jack Ross: My ultimate ambition is to lead Scotland.
Sunderland coach Jack Ross explains that his “ultimate ambition” is to become the Scottish coach at some point.
The 42-year-old is delighted to take on the challenge of reviving the Northeast club, which is currently in third place in League 1, with three points from the leader.
He rallied the Stadium of Light this summer after taking St Mirren to the Scottish Premier League last season.
“I wanted to play for my country as a player.
I was selected for Division B and that’s it,” Ross told BBC Scotland’s Sportsound.
“But I grew up following Scotland’s games at Hampden with my father and it’s something I’ve never forgotten.
This opportunity would only come, however, if I succeeded in managing the club.”
Ross' predecessors as Sunderland's coach are Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former Alloa Athletic coach says he has not hesitated to stand behind such iconic names in such a big club, having already declined the proposals of Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
“For me, the success of the moment will be measured in light of the question ‘can I bring this club back to the Premier League?’
Due to the structure and infrastructure of this club, it undoubtedly belongs to the Premier League,” he added.
“It’s not easy to get there, but I would probably consider myself a success here only if I manage to get the club back there.”
Ross has only three years as a coach, after a stint as an assistant at Dumbarton and 15 months as a Hearts coach.
He then helped Alloa recover from a third-division relegation and transformed St Mirren, who was on the verge of relegation, into a major championship winner the following season.
Ross feels more comfortable now than during his career at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
Taking care of Alloa “was probably a real crossroads,” he recalls.
“I really felt that being a coach was better than playing.
This seems strange because I did well, I made a good living, and I took advantage of some appreciable peaks.
But sometimes playing is difficult.
There are a lot of details to settle each week.
