Europe wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team won the 2018 Ryder Cup by beating the U.S. team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at the National Golf near Paris, France.
The United States has now lost six times in a row on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the title when the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn crossed the bar of 14.5 points needed to beat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who found himself in trouble for most of the tournament, plunged his starting shot into the water at the 16th hole in par-3, handing his duel to Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari excelled in all his rounds, becoming one of four players to have ever reached 5-0-0 since the current format of the tournament, whose first edition dates back to 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was dismissed 5 to 4 by the least well-placed player of the European team, Thorbjorn Olesen, from Denmark.
The best golfer in the world, Dustin Johnson, bowed 2 and 1 against England's Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
A veteran of eight Ryder Cups, Spanish Sergio Garcia has become the European champion of all time with a total of 25.5 career points.
“In general, I don’t cry, but today, it’s stronger than me.
It was an eventful year.
I am so grateful to Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm so happy, so happy to get the cup back.
What matters is the team, and I’m happy to have been able to help them,” Garcia said after the European victory.
He passes the baton to his compatriot John Ram who beat American golf legend Tiger Woods 2-1 in singles last Sunday.
