Woods has lost his four games in France and now holds a 13-21-3 career record in the Ryder Cup.
A surprising statistic for one of the greatest golfers of all time, who won 14 major titles, just behind Jack Nicklaus.
The U.S. team struggled all weekend to find the fairways, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played high-level golf throughout the tournament.
U.S. captain Jim Furyk commented after a disappointing performance about his team: “I’m proud of these guys, they fought.
This morning we had a moment where we put pressure on Europe.
We've given up.
Hat to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 players played very well.
We’re going to get together, I’m going to work with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup committee and we’re going to move forward.
I love these 12 guys and I'm proud to be a captain.
We have to bow.
We have exceeded ourselves.”
Red tide info point: Concentrations drop in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in some areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – leading to fears of declining concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee County.
There are islets about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in fewer locations than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or offshore, medium concentrations in Charlotte County or low concentrations in that bottom county, and low concentrations in that bottom county.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory irritation has been reported in northwestern Florida in the past week.
